photo.title: Blue Hour in San Francisco

description._content: One evening after work while in San Francisco, I went on a solo photowalk and was just sort of meandering. San Fran is a great town for that. There are things to photograph on nearly every corner. I made my way over to the gate at the entrance to Chinatown, and nearby was the Grand Hyatt. I had read that there was a restaurant or bar sort of thing at the top, and that the view is great. So, with camera and tripod in hand, I just walked into the hotel, made a beeline for the elevators, and hit the button for the top floor. When I got out of the elevators, I found myself in a very busy place. All the best tables were taken and it was crowded - but I guess I should have expected that. It's not like they wait for me to arrive and just clear out. Luckily I saw a little alcove off to the side - it looked like an area where they used to have pay phones, which I guess people don't really need anymore. It was small, but most importantly it was empty and offered this wonderful view. I quickly set up the tripod and snapped some shots, before the host decided it was a bad idea. Single image, 8 second exposure taken at f/5. photo.title: San Francisco Painted Ladies 11

description._content:
The Victorian Painted Ladies off Alamo Square, with the downtown San Francisco skyline in the distance, including the Transamerica Pyramid.

The Painted Ladies are a row of Victorian houses that sit on Alamo Square, in the Haight-Ashbury area of San Francisco.

The group of six houses were built in 1894 and are Italianate in style, though they each have a gable, which is not usual in that style of architecture.

Most of San Francisco’ Victorian houses were pulled down in the 20th century, but this row survived and gained its pastel-coloured paintwork in the 1960s from the hippie era.

The view looking down on the houses from Alamo Square is magnificent, with the downtown skyline in the distance rising up above them. I quite happily spent a few hours here just admiring in the view in one of the few places in the whole of San Francisco that seemed to avoid the fog and be bathed in sunshine instead.

photo.title: An Auspicious Horizon

description._content: This image of the gorgeous San Francisco skyline at night  is the first skyline I captured with my Nikon D90. This was my first visit to the city by the bay and after hearing so much hype and great things over the years, I can truly say San Francisco did not disappoint. It is an amazing city with a wealth of things to experience and enjoy. I have been to both Los Angeles and San Diego a zillion times and left San Francisco much more impressed and amazed. Keep in mind, growing up near Seattle, San Francisco probably appealed to me more because Seattle and San Francisco have some obvious similarities in their topography, make-up, and history (both gold rush cities). This image was captured on Telegraph Hill with Coit Tower resting behind me and in the center of the image is the famous landmark, the Transamerica Pyramid. I plan on visiting this city several more times and was so impressed to be able to finally capture this image. Enjoy!

From Computer hardware, to networking and internet social networking they are all here.  And the city has a high-tech look too which feels 'cutting edge' when you are in the middle of it. And there are a few nice views to be had too!

photo.title: 365035 - San Francisco's Pyramid

description._content: Day Thirty Five (35) 100315 First full day in San Francisco today, I had arisen early to drop the car back while the better half enjoyed some additional sleep. Once she had arisen we stopped into a dinner for a full and I mean full breakfast, a serving of hash brown (not your typical Macca’s hash), continental omelette (yes I’ll eat egg) and English muffin, large enough to be considered a large dinner at home, there was about 1/3 sent back. After breaky we hoped on the usually tourist mecca, the city hop on, hop off tourist bus, in all seriousness these tours are brilliant in getting to know your way around a new city, getting your bearings and finding out a little bit about the place on the way. While turning into Columbus Ave., San Francisco on the bus you are noted to turn around and take note of the tallest building in San Francisco, the Transamerica Pyramid which stands at 260m all as we have become to learn that is 850ft, along with it’s height it is also it’s unique pyramid shape that makes it so recognisable across the city landscape. Hand held, seated on open deck tour bus seat twisted round, trying to get the trolley bus cables dissecting the building evenly. Other shot in today’s mix www.flickr.com/photos/youngie11/4458762657/

description._content:
The Downtown San Francisco skyline seen from Municipal Pier, with Coit Tower on the left and the Transamerica Pyramid on the right.

Coit Tower stands on top of Telegraph Hill and provides views out across the whole of the San Francisco Bay Area, from the Golden Gate Bridge round to the Bay Bridge and whole of the city itself.

The tower is 212ft tall and was built from money left behind by Lillie Coit to improve the city when she died in 1929.

The structure resembles a fire hose nozzle and Lillie was a popular figure among the fire service in the city, having been involved with them her entire life.

photo.title: San Francisco Painted Ladies 19

description._content:
The San Francisco downtown skyline rises above the Painted Ladies houses off Alamo Square.

The Painted Ladies are a row of Victorian houses that sit on Alamo Square, in the Haight-Ashbury area of San Francisco.

The group of six houses were built in 1894 and are Italianate in style, though they each have a gable, which is not usual in that style of architecture.

Most of San Francisco’ Victorian houses were pulled down in the 20th century, but this row survived and gained its pastel-coloured paintwork in the 1960s from the hippie era.

The view looking down on the houses from Alamo Square is magnificent, with the downtown skyline in the distance rising up above them. I quite happily spent a few hours here just admiring in the view in one of the few places in the whole of San Francisco that seemed to avoid the fog and be bathed in sunshine instead.

photo.title: Towers of San Francisco

description._content:
Looking down Pier 39 at the City of San Francisco. with Coit Tower (left) and the Transamerica Pyramid (right) standing out of the urban skyline.

Coit Tower stands on top of Telegraph Hill and provides views out across the whole of the San Francisco Bay Area, from the Golden Gate Bridge round to the Bay Bridge and whole of the city itself.

The tower is 212ft tall and was built from money left behind by Lillie Coit to improve the city when she died in 1929.

The structure resembles a fire hose nozzle and Lillie was a popular figure among the fire service in the city, having been involved with them her entire life.

Pier 39 is one of the most developed piers in the whole of the Fisherman’s Wharf area of San Francisco. It is home to the Aquarium of the Bay and numerous shops and businesses, as well as numerous sea lions, who laze on platforms to the side of the pier and attract many onlookers throughout the day.

The sea lions just ‘appeared’ after the 1989 earthquake that hit the city and have refused to go anywhere since, preferring to bask in the sun and occasionally swim off to get food.
